          "text": "Perfect! I've completed the analysis of the Grafana alerting evaluation scheduler. Here's a summary of my findings:\n\n## Key Findings\n\nI've identified the Go source files in grafana/grafana that implement the alerting evaluation scheduler and detect evaluation cycle overruns:\n\n### Main Files:\n\n1. **pkg/services/ngalert/schedule/schedule.go** - The primary scheduler implementation containing:\n   - `Run()` - Entry point that starts the scheduler\n   - `schedulePeriodic()` - Main event loop that processes ticks from the ticker\n   - `processTick()` - Determines which rules should be evaluated on each tick\n   - `runJobFn()` - **Where overrun detection occurs** (line 438)\n\n2. **pkg/services/ngalert/schedule/ticker/ticker.go** - The periodic ticker that drives evaluations\n   - `New()` - Creates the ticker\n   - `run()` - Implements the ticker event loop\n\n3. **pkg/services/ngalert/schedule/alert_rule.go** - Individual alert rule evaluation\n   - `Run()` - Evaluation routine for each alert rule\n\n4. **pkg/services/ngalert/schedule/recording_rule.go** - Recording rule evaluation (similar structure)\n\n### Overrun Detection:\n\nThe scheduler detects when an evaluation cycle overruns its time budget in the `runJobFn()` method. When an alert rule evaluation takes longer than the scheduler's base interval, the next scheduled evaluation is dropped. This is logged as a warning:\n\n```\n\"Tick dropped because alert rule evaluation is too slow\"\n```\n\nThis occurs at line 438 in `schedule.go` when the evaluation channel already has an unprocessed evaluation from the previous cycle.\n\nThe answer has been saved to `/workspace/answer.json` with complete details about the files, symbols, execution chain, and detailed narrative explanation.",
